  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling vacant land looks simple from the outside. No pool safety form, no smoke alarms, no styling, no open homes walked through a lived-in house. In practice the process is different enough from a standard home sale that sellers who treat it the same way usually come away with a slower campaign, a weaker price, or a surprise tax bill. This guide walks through what actually changes.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What counts as vacant land</h2>

      <p>For sale purposes, vacant land in Brisbane typically falls into one of four categories. First, unimproved residential lots in new or recent subdivisions, where no dwelling has ever been constructed. Second, rural or semi-rural acreage lots, often on the city fringe. Third, infill blocks in established suburbs after a knock-down, where the previous dwelling has been demolished and the land is waiting for a new build. Fourth, lots still subject to community titles scheme registration or awaiting subdivision approval, where the legal title is not yet finalised.</p>

      <p>Each category has specific contract implications. Newly subdivided and community-titled lots often cannot be legally transferred until registration is complete, which affects settlement timing and contract structure. Infill blocks may carry obligations from the demolition, such as site cleanliness, capping of services, or unresolved council consents. Rural lots may carry vegetation, bushfire, or rural planning overlays that do not apply to a typical residential block. Get the category right before you list, because it drives most of the other decisions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the buyer pool differs</h2>

      <p>The buyer pool for vacant land is narrower than for a completed home, and the buyers are more calculated. An owner-occupier looking for a family home is typically running an emotional process: they walk through a house, picture their life in it, and bid on how it makes them feel. A land buyer is running a build feasibility: they weigh block attributes against a build budget, compare two or three sites on paper, and decide based on numbers.</p>

      <p>Three buyer types dominate. Owner-occupiers planning to build their own home often take longer to commit because the purchase is only the first step of a longer process. Developers run spec-build or multi-dwelling calculations and move fast on blocks that fit their pipeline. Investors hold land for capital growth and move deliberately on price.</p>

      <p>Because the pool is narrower, campaign length can run longer than equivalent completed homes. It is not a failure of the campaign; it is a structural feature of the market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the marketing differs</h2>

      <p>The marketing pack for vacant land looks nothing like a standard home listing. The hero photo is usually a drone aerial showing the block, the street, and the surrounding context. Ground-level shots of the block from multiple angles, a clear view of the street frontage, and photos of adjacent developments or reference homes help buyers visualise what could be built.</p>

      <p>Site plans, contour surveys, and soil test reports are central rather than optional. A serious buyer will want to see all three before making an offer, and providing them in the marketing pack removes friction, shortens buyer due diligence, and signals that the block is genuinely ready to build on.</p>

      <p>Typical campaigns are shorter, more targeted, and more document-heavy than house campaigns. Open-home style inspections rarely work because there is nothing to walk through; private site visits by appointment with the agent are the norm. The seller should expect the campaign to feel quieter on the surface than a house campaign, even if buyer interest is strong.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the contract differs</h2>

      <p>In Queensland, the standard contract for vacant land is the REIQ Contract for Residential Lots in a Community Titles Scheme (if the lot is in a scheme) or the REIQ Contract for Houses and Residential Land with the appropriate dwelling and inclusions left blank. Vacant land contracts do not include pool safety or smoke alarm disclosures, because there is no dwelling. Body corporate disclosure only applies if the land sits within a community titles scheme.</p>

      <p>The conditions that matter are different too. Buyers often want clauses focused on soil tests (geotechnical reports), surveys, services availability, and in some cases development approvals, rather than the building and pest condition that dominates house contracts. Some buyers will make the contract conditional on achieving a development approval for a specific design, which creates a longer conditional period and requires careful drafting.</p>

      <p>A conveyancer or solicitor with specific vacant-land experience is worth having. The standard forms are the same, but the practical conditions and the due-diligence clauses require judgement the seller may not have.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What land sellers should prepare</h2>

      <p>Four documents should be in hand before listing. A current land survey identifying boundaries, any encroachments, and any registered easements. A geotechnical soil test report if available: it costs the seller a few hundred dollars and saves the buyer the same, which usually accelerates the sale and strengthens the seller's position on price. A services report showing what is at the boundary (power, water, sewer, NBN or other broadband) and what the buyer will need to connect. Any council approvals that apply to the lot, such as pre-approved plans for a specific design, development approvals for a subdivision yet to be finalised, or operational works approvals.</p>

      <p>This preparation pack is the most impactful thing a land seller can do. It reduces buyer due diligence from weeks to days, narrows the range of conditional clauses the buyer will request, and lets the campaign move at the pace the seller wants rather than the pace the buyer's consultants set.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How valuation works differently</h2>

      <p>Valuing vacant land is not about backing out a house price. It is about comparing recent sales of similar-sized lots in the area, adjusted for frontage, aspect, contour, services availability, and any easements or overlays.</p>

      <p>If direct land comparables are thin, an indirect method is to take recent house sales in the suburb and back out an estimate of the improvements value (what it would cost to rebuild the house new, minus depreciation). The remainder is an implied land value. This is a cruder approach and gives a range rather than a point estimate, but it is useful as a sanity check.</p>

      <p>The resulting numbers often look very different from headline suburb medians, which are dominated by house sales. Sellers relying on house-based medians to price land will usually overprice.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should ask their agent</h2>

      <p>Three questions separate agents who genuinely sell vacant land from agents who mostly sell houses. First, what is your direct experience selling vacant land in this suburb and the surrounding streets, and which lots have you listed and sold in the last twelve to twenty-four months? Second, who are the active buyers in this land price range right now, and do you have direct relationships with developers, builders, and buyer's agents who operate in the land market? Third, what do the most recent comparable land sales show about timing, price, and typical campaign length, and how should that shape my expectations?</p>

      <p>If the agent cannot answer all three with specifics, they are almost certainly a house specialist trying to extend into land. That can still work for a straightforward infill lot, but it rarely works for larger, rural, or development-oriented lots.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The CGT position</h2>

      <p>Vacant land is treated as a capital gains tax asset. The main residence exemption that applies to a family home does not apply to vacant land, even if the seller owns a house on a separate block nearby. A capital gain on the sale is typically taxable, with the standard CGT rules applying: cost base, indexed or discounted methods, partial discounts for assets held more than twelve months.</p>

      <p>Sellers should obtain tax advice before signing a contract, especially if the land was acquired at a low base many years ago, if it was received by gift or inheritance, or if it has been used intermittently for income-producing purposes (such as leasing to a neighbour for storage or grazing). The tax outcome can materially change the net result of the sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The GST position</h2>

      <p>Most individual sellers of vacant residential land do not pay GST, because the sale is a mere realisation of a capital asset rather than an enterprise activity. GST applies when the sale is part of a business or profit-making undertaking: typically sellers who have subdivided land, developed it, or acquired it with the intention of sub-dividing and on-selling.</p>

      <p>The line between a mere realisation and an enterprise activity is not always obvious. Subdividing an inherited family block and selling the pieces can tip a seller into the GST net in some circumstances. Specific advice from an accountant is important if the sale involves any development, subdivision, or sustained holding and servicing activity. Getting this wrong costs real money, because GST on vacant land can be twenty thousand to one hundred thousand dollars or more on a typical block.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The timing of the market</h2>

      <p>Vacant land activity often lags established home activity. When interest rates move, house prices respond first, and land prices follow with a three to six month delay. This is because buyers of land are typically already planning a build, and build decisions take longer to form than purchase decisions.</p>

      <p>Builder capacity and construction cost changes also affect how willing buyers are to commit. In periods of rising build costs, buyers become more cautious about locking in a block before they know what construction will cost. In periods of falling or stable build costs, land activity accelerates. Recent residential building approval and completion data, published by the ABS and the QBCC, gives sellers a leading indicator of land demand.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>

      <p>Selling vacant land in Brisbane requires a different playbook from selling a home. There are fewer emotional levers and more financial and technical ones. The preparation pack (survey, soil test, services, approvals) pays for itself in a faster campaign and stronger price. The valuation must be built from comparable land sales, not headline suburb medians. The contract, the CGT position, and the GST position all deserve specific professional advice before signing.</p>

      <p>Above all, choose an agent who demonstrably understands the land market: who has sold similar lots, who knows the active buyers, and who can speak fluently about zoning, services, and development feasibility. The right agent makes a structural difference to the outcome on vacant land, more so than for a standard house sale.</p>

